    "body": "### Problem\n\n`--listen` could be more convenient (DWIM) in the way it handles existing sockets. If a socket exists, Nvim just reports an error and fails to listen on it. But there are some cases where Nvim could automatically handle the situation.\n\nFollowup to https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/26053 , https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/30123\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n\n- When trying to start a server specified by `--listen` *or* `serverstart()`:\n    - [ref](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/26053#issuecomment-1813260697) if libuv supports socket state querying, check whether existing socket file is not in the `LISTEN` state and then remove it.\n- Alternatively: try to connect to the existing socket file.\n    - If the connect is refused or doesn't correctly respond to a Nvim RPC request, assume it's a dead server and destroy the socket. Then recreate a new one.\n    - If a RPC response is returned, show an error informing the user that the socket is already in use by another Nvim.\n- Log a message at \"info\" level when this happens.",
